ent. If you=E2=80=99re reading this, then, don=E2=80=99t do whatever you ju=
st did again.=C2=A0
I was planning to put my head down and write a piece to send like I do ever=
y Monday, and I was about 60% done, plenty far enough to finish if I spent =
most of the day Sunday like I always do, but we had his birthday party yest=
erday, and our friends and family were in town, and I realized that enjoyin=
g that with him and Puja and everyone was so much more important than rushi=
ng back to the computer to get a normal newsletter out.=C2=A0
A year ago, I would have been terrified to go off course for a week when mo=
mentum is strong. I feel deeply accountable to all of you to send a newslet=
ter out every week, to the sponsors who make Not Boring part of their marke=
ting plans, to the founders I=E2=80=99ve backed and to the LPs who=E2=80=99=
ve backed me. The sheer numbers on that side of the aisle are overwhelming.=
 It can throw my perspective out of whack, push me to work seven days a wee=
k every week. But there=E2=80=99s only one person out there depending on me=
 for his survival; the rest of you will be fine for a week.=C2=A0
Growing a business and growing a kid in the same year has been an incredibl=
e, intense ride. Instead of a normal piece this week, I thought I=E2=80=99d=
 reflect a little bit. It might be fun to read this together in four, nine,=
 twelve, fifteen, or seventeen years, on some big birthday milestone in the=
 future. Plus, I=E2=80=99ve read a lot of pieces about being a working mom,=
 but fewer about being a working dad. Thanks to work from home, more dads a=
re getting to be a bigger part of their kids=E2=80=99 lives, which is both =
the greatest thing in the world, and hard. I=E2=80=99m throwing my thoughts=
 in the ring in case they=E2=80=99re helpful to anyone trying to balance it=
 all and feeling constantly behind. Me too.=C2=A0
(As if he knew I was writing a full Not Boring on Monday morning for the fi=
rst time ever, or maybe out of excitement for his birthday, or probably bec=
ause he had pizza and ice cream for the first time yesterday, Dev decided t=
o stay up most of the night last night for the first time in a long time. I=
 blame any cheesiness below on dad brain.)=C2=A0
First things first, I know we=E2=80=99re incredibly fortunate. The most ama=
zing thing about this past year has been that we=E2=80=99ve both gotten to =
spend it at home -- whether home was in New Jersey with Puja=E2=80=99s pare=
nts, at the shore with mine, or back in Brooklyn -- with the buddy. I alway=
s just assumed that whenever I had a kid, I=E2=80=99d have to leave in the =
morning, go to an office every day, and try to make it back in time to read=
 him a book and put him to bed. That=E2=80=99s if I was lucky and didn=E2=
=80=99t have to travel.=C2=A0
My dad had to travel for work all the time when I was little. A couple week=
s ago, he told me the story of flying to Miami for a morning meeting, flyin=
g home in the afternoon to take me and my sister to the St. Dennis Fair in =
the evening, and then waking up the next morning at 4am to get back on the =
plane to go down to Miami for the next day=E2=80=99s meetings. That wasn=E2=
=80=99t unique; I distinctly recall day trips to Germany. At the time, when=
 I was like ten, I thought that was so cool. Who else=E2=80=99s dad popped =
over to Europe for the day? Now=E2=80=A6 I can=E2=80=99t even begin to fath=
om how exhausting that must have been. And I can=E2=80=99t imagine how chal=
lenging it was for my mom to raise me, and then my sister and brother, whil=
e working, and then getting her PhD and starting her own business at the sa=
me time, while my dad was traveling. Every bit of work ethic I have comes f=
rom both of them, and I feel very soft when I think about how much they did=
 versus how much I do. Getting on a plane every few months, or watching Dev=
 on my own for an afternoon, and then sitting in front of a computer and wr=
iting wipes me out.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s hard to fully appreciate your parents until you become one.=C2=
=A0
Either way, it was a foregone conclusion in my mind that I=E2=80=99d miss t=
hings like first words, first steps, first everything. That=E2=80=99s just =
what working parents do. If you want to provide for your kid, that means no=
t seeing them sometimes, and trying to be successful enough that you could =
maybe set your own schedule at some point when they=E2=80=99re a little old=
er, maybe even retire early. COVID has been terrible for a billion reasons,=
 but personally, the silver lining has been not needing to make that trade-=
off. Work and home are the same thing.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ve gotten really lucky. At the beginning of the pandemic, I=E2=
=80=99d quit my job, shuttered the company I was trying to build, and was a=
n unemployed newsletter writer with fewer than 500 readers, all free, and n=
o income. We=E2=80=99d just found out we were going to have the baby future=
ly known as Dev. It was a scary time to bring a kid into the world, globall=
y and locally. Puja was thinking about taking a new job at a startup, and w=
e had to spend a lot of time thinking about whether it made sense to give u=
p her healthcare with a kid on the way. But we got to live with Puja=E2=80=
=99s parents when Dev was born, and spend a lot of time with my family. I g=
ot to work from the basement rent-free while I was income-free. And I got t=
o pop upstairs every time I wanted to see the little man.=C2=A0
Dev got to spend most of his first year really getting to know his grandpar=
ents, and his Aunt Meg and Uncle Dan. Now that we=E2=80=99re back in Brookl=
yn, Meg has come home from Ghana a few times and gotten to spend time with =
him; she stayed with us a couple times in the past week and wakes up with h=
im in the morning like a saint. Dan and Sienna live in New York and come ov=
er every Sunday. Puja=E2=80=99s parents and/or mine are here practically ev=
ery week.=C2=A0
Balancing everything is still challenging. I sent a newsletter four days af=
ter Dev was born and have worked practically seven days a week straight thr=
ough. In April, I launched Not Boring Capital just to up the degree of diff=
iculty. I=E2=80=99ve never worked harder in my life. I feel like I=E2=80=99=
m dropping balls everywhere -- when I=E2=80=99m working, I=E2=80=99m not be=
ing as good of a dad or husband as I could be; when I=E2=80=99m taking a br=
eak at 4pm on a Tuesday to take him to the playground with Puja, I=E2=80=99=
m not working hard enough.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a reason that world-changing companies are often built by y=
oung people: it requires a maniacal focus and the ability to put everything=
 into a company. I=E2=80=99m not willing to do that anymore. I=E2=80=99m co=
nstantly turning down in-person meetings, dinners, and other time-consuming=
 things that would probably be good for my career but would mean less time =
with Dev and Puja. At least when the baby is little, I think you can choose=
 two of three:
Good parent
Career growth
Social Life
I=E2=80=99m trying to be a good dad and grow Not Boring and Not Boring Capi=
tal. That means trading off a social life for now, which I=E2=80=99m totall=
y cool with, and not being nearly as responsive as I should be to email, te=
xts, DMs, etc=E2=80=A6 which I need to get better at. If your email is sitt=
ing somewhere in my inbox unread, I=E2=80=99m sorry =F0=9F=98=AC
Puja is an absolute hero -- an incredible mom, a natural, on top of everyth=
ing when I=E2=80=99m absent-minded, consulting, running her own company [ht=
tps://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEFuxCAMRU8zLCNiYJIsWHTTa0QGPAkaAikhTdPT=
l5ksKlm25C_r-X-LhaaUT72mrbBXG8u5ko50bIFKocz2jfLonW7v0AslB-a0dG2veua38ZGJFvR=
Bl7wTW3cTvMXiU3xfcA6KzfphkIRBKQcQDpwFYRWSMW4QEnuFFxd35yla0vRN-UyRWNBzKet2Ex=
83-Kx1HEczUwgprZSxpNz8nL91z7wGDm3FyRbkoIYGGomgnOAAnbHYdaIpnJ9fi5tuki8TNNtut=
oL22di0sKxjKiZlH1_yc8aFwluohsY6lz36co4U0QRyl9dyRfZ2P04UXx-RG7HUoIQQqu257Pn9=
8lbDkNBCP4iOVbJL9Sr-Q_8AlZ6EWQ], and still making time to hang out with fri=
ends and family. She does more than I do, actually does three out of three,=
 and makes it look easy, even though I know it=E2=80=99s not. She blows me =
away. I=E2=80=99m so happy Dev is picking up all of her incredible qualitie=
s (including, thankfully, looking more like her than me).=C2=A0
The first time he was on Invest Like the Best [https://email.mg2.substack.c=
om/c/eJxFkctuxCAMRb8m7CYiPPJYsKhU9TciA-4MHQIpOK3y92VmFpUs27Jl3atjB4TXXE6z50=
rskVY6dzQJf2tEIizsqFjW4M0willqtTBvlB9mPbNQ18-CuEGIhsqBbD9sDA4o5PS84FxodjMLC=
OSae-RcjeMEs1NCS23HRTspOL504fABk0ODP1jOnJBFcyPaayffOvHR4iuH5HLMtR61d3lrI9xD=
zR5ra8Ugp2XgqrW3kO4BLx4ILh5dqM1QvUDyFwv1jmQhxk5-ENhOvlOBVF0JO7FgBBdDs60GoRa=
99KJXILSXXIjJOpgm2RPn5_fmr53i21X09bCVwN0fflgxKZPNJaTH-n6DDeNz0cCsrW5HCnSumM=
BG9C9m9EL_pLheMWFpL_ErUAMupdTDzNXMxxejBlWJQcyLnFhT9rldpX_RP8aqm4c], Sam Hin=
kie said, =E2=80=9CI think it's the single biggest decision of your life an=
d I don't think it's close, who you choose to spend your life with.=E2=80=
=9D There are a couple of reasons for that: first, because you=E2=80=99ll s=
pend the most time with that person, and second, because that person will c=
ontribute 50% to your kids=E2=80=99 =E2=80=A6 everything. Your kids will be=
 half you, and half your partner. When I listened to that podcast, we weren=
=E2=80=99t parents yet, so I kind of got it conceptually, but it=E2=80=99s =
really struck me over the past year how right he was. I see so much of Puja=
 in Dev, and love watching her be his mom more than anything.=C2=A0
And then there=E2=80=99s Dev himself. The kid is unbelievable. When you=E2=
=80=99re pregnant, everyone tells you how hard it=E2=80=99s going to be. It=
=E2=80=99s kind of like pledging a fraternity, they say, the best thing tha=
t you=E2=80=99ll never want to do again or something. They tell you that fo=
r the first few months, the kid will just be a blob. That it=E2=80=99s bori=
ng. I don=E2=80=99t think we felt that way for a single day. He=E2=80=99s h=
ad his own personality from the beginning, and even when he was just a coup=
le weeks old, you could tell that there was something going on behind those=
 wise brown eyes.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s all gone into hyperdrive recently, though. Even though he=E2=
=80=99s only one, you can already tell that he=E2=80=99s kind and funny and=
 smart and driven. He shares his pacifier and his bottle with us even thoug=
h he wants them so badly. He=E2=80=99s the most determined kid I=E2=80=99ve=
 ever seen. He won=E2=80=99t stop until he gets what he wants. He laughs, h=
e walks, he=E2=80=99s starting to talk. Last week, he parroted blue, yellow=
, and notebook (we=E2=80=99ve been watching some Blue=E2=80=99s Clues). He =
says mama and dada like he knows what he=E2=80=99s talking about. He=E2=80=
=99s like a little grownup in a baby body.=C2=A0
Even now, just a year in, I have an idea of what he=E2=80=99ll be like as a=
 kid and even kind of as a grownup, which is wild. I can=E2=80=99t wait to =
see the little man he turns into, and then the bigger man he turns into aft=
er that. When I see teenagers starting companies or making NFTs or doing an=
ything impressive-beyond-their-years, my first thought is that Dev will be =
doing some really incredible things really young. When I see companies like=
 Primer [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUEmOhDAMfE3niEwWlkMOc5lvoCwGo=
